JAMES GILLAM: There are certain
rules to tunnel warfare.

256
00:14:37,133 --> 00:14:39,832
Don't turn on the light

257
00:14:39,932 --> 00:14:43,000
unless you're really, really,
really sure you're alone.

258
00:14:43,100 --> 00:14:46,700
Use your senses.

259
00:14:46,799 --> 00:14:49,899
Do your first killing
as quietly as you can.

260
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,066
That means don't shoot.

261
00:14:53,365 --> 00:14:56,133
I chased somebody into a tunnel,

262
00:14:56,232 --> 00:15:01,500
met them at a bend in the
corner, in the dark.

263
00:15:01,600 --> 00:15:03,100
I thought I was alone

264
00:15:03,200 --> 00:15:06,399
and then I smelled their breath.

265
00:15:06,500 --> 00:15:12,500
And we had a wrestling match in the dark.

266
00:15:12,600 --> 00:15:14,966
And I got the upper hand

267
00:15:15,066 --> 00:15:18,299
and crushed this person's trachea,

268
00:15:18,399 --> 00:15:21,033
held him down while he died...

269
00:15:22,666 --> 00:15:24,566
...and then got out.

270
00:15:27,299 --> 00:15:30,000
I beat and strangled someone to death

271
00:15:30,100 --> 00:15:31,899
in a tunnel

272
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:33,966
in the dark.

273
00:15:34,066 --> 00:15:35,665
Um...

274
00:15:35,765 --> 00:15:38,200
But that wasn't the only casualty.

275
00:15:38,299 --> 00:15:42,633
The other casualty was the
civilized version of me.

276
00:15:51,466 --> 00:15:53,633
(gunfire)

277
00:15:59,466 --> 00:16:01,232
(gunfire continuing)

278
00:16:01,332 --> 00:16:03,066
(shouting)

279
00:16:03,166 --> 00:16:06,066
NARRATOR: April 1969

280
00:16:06,166 --> 00:16:09,133
marked the high point of
American military commitment

281
00:16:09,232 --> 00:16:10,666
to South Vietnam.

282
00:16:10,765 --> 00:16:18,133
543,482 men and women were now in country,

283
00:16:18,232 --> 00:16:22,265
and tens of thousands more were stationed

284
00:16:22,365 --> 00:16:25,299
at airbases and aboard
ships beyond its borders.

285
00:16:26,600 --> 00:16:31,265
40,794 had died.

286
00:16:31,365 --> 00:16:36,299
And more than $70 billion had been spent.

287
00:16:36,399 --> 00:16:39,899
(explosion in distance)

288
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:42,399
That spring, a new battle

289
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:44,600
caught the attention of
the American public,

290
00:16:44,700 --> 00:16:49,399
a struggle to take still
another numbered hill...

291
00:16:49,500 --> 00:16:53,133
Hill 937 on military maps.

292
00:16:53,232 --> 00:16:55,200
CHET HUNTLEY: For nine days,

293
00:16:55,299 --> 00:16:57,242
American and South Vietnamese
troops have been trying

294
00:16:57,266 --> 00:16:59,200
to take a mountain near the Laotian border,

295
00:16:59,299 --> 00:17:02,133
and ten times they have been thrown back.

296
00:17:02,232 --> 00:17:03,500
(booming, shouting)

297
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:07,465
(gunfire)

298
00:17:17,532 --> 00:17:19,732
(shouting over radio)

299
00:17:26,633 --> 00:17:29,232
The casualties have been so high...

300
00:17:29,333 --> 00:17:32,599
50 Americans and 250 North
Vietnamese killed...

301
00:17:32,700 --> 00:17:35,333
that the mountain has come to
be known as "Hamburger Hill."

302
00:17:35,432 --> 00:17:39,066
Today, another 600 allied troops
were thrown into the battle.

303
00:17:39,165 --> 00:17:41,732
(helicopter blades whirring)

304
00:17:41,833 --> 00:17:44,200
(gunfire)

305
00:17:44,299 --> 00:17:47,000
(explosion, screaming)

306
00:17:50,865 --> 00:17:53,165
NARRATOR: A weary G.I. told a reporter

307
00:17:53,266 --> 00:17:55,365
that his battalion commander

308
00:17:55,465 --> 00:18:00,333
"won't stop until he kills
every damn one of us."

309
00:18:00,432 --> 00:18:01,732
(explosion, gunfire)

310
00:18:06,700 --> 00:18:08,965
After 11 days of fighting,

311
00:18:09,066 --> 00:18:11,766
the Battle for Hamburger Hill ended.

312
00:18:13,232 --> 00:18:15,932
56 Americans died.

313
00:18:16,032 --> 00:18:20,333
420 more were wounded.

314
00:18:20,432 --> 00:18:23,965
A week later, the Americans
abandoned the hill,

315
00:18:24,066 --> 00:18:26,965
just as they had abandoned
so many other hills

316
00:18:27,066 --> 00:18:31,599
they had taken at great cost
over the years in Vietnam.

317
00:18:33,732 --> 00:18:36,633
General, could you explain for
us again the strategy involved

318
00:18:36,732 --> 00:18:39,732
in the decision to withdraw American troops

319
00:18:39,833 --> 00:18:43,032
after they had taken Hill
937, or Hamburger Hill?

320
00:18:45,200 --> 00:18:49,099
No piece of ground, as such,

321
00:18:49,200 --> 00:18:51,599
is important to us.

322
00:18:51,700 --> 00:18:53,432
HUNTLEY: In the United States Senate,

323
00:18:53,532 --> 00:18:55,333
Senator Kennedy of Massachusetts delivered

324
00:18:55,432 --> 00:18:57,232
a brief speech criticizing what he called

325
00:18:57,333 --> 00:19:00,266
a "senseless and
irresponsible military pride

326
00:19:00,365 --> 00:19:02,766
"in which American men
are sent to their deaths

327
00:19:02,865 --> 00:19:05,599
in pointless battles like
this one for Hamburger Hill."

328
00:19:05,700 --> 00:19:07,799
Kennedy called upon President Nixon

329
00:19:07,900 --> 00:19:10,032
to issue new orders to
commanders in Vietnam

330
00:19:10,133 --> 00:19:11,665
to halt such actions

331
00:19:11,766 --> 00:19:13,566
and he charged that they contradict

332
00:19:13,665 --> 00:19:15,000
the president's stated intentions

333
00:19:15,099 --> 00:19:16,799
of seeking a negotiated peace.

334
00:19:19,633 --> 00:19:22,900
NARRATOR: There had been more
deadly weeks during the war,

335
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:27,365
costlier battles, larger
numbers of casualties.

336
00:19:27,465 --> 00:19:33,665
But more and more Americans
seemed to have had enough.

337
00:19:33,766 --> 00:19:36,133
The following month, Li fe magazine

338
00:19:36,232 --> 00:19:38,266
published the names and photographs

339
00:19:38,365 --> 00:19:41,165
of all 242 Americans

340
00:19:41,266 --> 00:19:45,133
who had died in combat in just one week.

341
00:19:45,232 --> 00:19:49,066
For the first time, in a
national publication,

342
00:19:49,165 --> 00:19:53,032
casualty statistics came with human faces.

343
00:19:55,932 --> 00:19:58,665
The only way they could
measure success in Vietnam

344
00:19:58,766 --> 00:20:00,865
was, was was kill ratios...

345
00:20:00,965 --> 00:20:03,133
how many of them versus how many of us.

346
00:20:03,232 --> 00:20:05,400
Well, the only thing that's important

347
00:20:05,500 --> 00:20:07,799
to the American people is the "us."

348
00:20:07,900 --> 00:20:11,465
You know, if there's three
us dead, that's the number.

349
00:20:11,566 --> 00:20:14,700
Not 30, you know, Vietnamese dead.

350
00:20:14,799 --> 00:20:17,865
And, so, politically, an attrition strategy

351
00:20:17,965 --> 00:20:20,133
just can't last very long.

352
00:20:20,232 --> 00:20:21,665
We don't care what the ratio is,

353
00:20:21,766 --> 00:20:23,008
we just want the absolute number

354
00:20:23,032 --> 00:20:25,665
of how many American kids died.

355
00:20:25,766 --> 00:20:29,032
NARRATOR: A Gallup poll now
found that most Americans

356
00:20:29,133 --> 00:20:32,900
believed Vietnam had been a mistake.

357
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:35,965
Richard Nixon knew he needed
to signal to the public

358
00:20:36,066 --> 00:20:38,299
that an end was in sight.

359
00:20:40,165 --> 00:20:43,633
The National Security
Council had warned Nixon

360
00:20:43,732 --> 00:20:45,766
that the Joint Chiefs of Staff,

361
00:20:45,865 --> 00:20:48,532
the secretaries of state and defense,

362
00:20:48,633 --> 00:20:53,566
the C.I.A., and the U.S. Embassy in Saigon

363
00:20:53,665 --> 00:20:56,732
all privately agreed that without U.S.
combat troops,

364
00:20:56,833 --> 00:20:58,432
the South Vietnamese

365
00:20:58,532 --> 00:21:03,099
"cannot now, or in the foreseeable future,

366
00:21:03,200 --> 00:21:05,299
"stand up to both Viet Cong

367
00:21:05,400 --> 00:21:09,032
and sizeable North Vietnamese forces."

368
00:21:09,133 --> 00:21:11,066
Nonetheless,

369
00:21:11,165 --> 00:21:14,232
Secretary of Defense Melvin Laird said,

370
00:21:14,333 --> 00:21:17,766
the war was now to be "Vietnamized."

371
00:21:17,865 --> 00:21:21,500
Saigon's troops would gradually
take over responsibility

372
00:21:21,599 --> 00:21:24,133
for engaging the enemy.

373
00:21:24,232 --> 00:21:27,333
It would be General Creighton Abrams' task

374
00:21:27,432 --> 00:21:29,700
to ready the ARVN for that role,

375
00:21:29,799 --> 00:21:32,500
and to make sure that American casualties

376
00:21:32,599 --> 00:21:34,732
were held down in the interim.

377
00:21:34,833 --> 00:21:38,200
("The Letter" by The Box
Tops starts playing)

378
00:21:38,299 --> 00:21:43,500
Meanwhile, American troops
would start to go home.

379
00:21:43,599 --> 00:21:46,432
♪ Gimme a ticket for an aeroplane ♪

380
00:21:46,532 --> 00:21:48,799
♪ Ain't got time to take a fast train ♪

381
00:21:48,900 --> 00:21:50,540
DUONG VAN MAI ELLIOTT: When Nixon came in

382
00:21:50,566 --> 00:21:54,400
and he announced the phase withdrawal,

383
00:21:54,500 --> 00:21:56,932
turning over the fighting
to the Vietnamese,

384
00:21:57,032 --> 00:21:59,465
which was something the
French had tried before.

385
00:21:59,566 --> 00:22:01,333
They call itjaunissement...

386
00:22:01,432 --> 00:22:04,700
yellowizing the war.

387
00:22:04,799 --> 00:22:10,833
We knew that the Vietnamese Army
was not up to fighting this war.

388
00:22:10,932 --> 00:22:13,400
If they couldn't do it with the Americans,

389
00:22:13,500 --> 00:22:16,566
how were they going to do
it without the Americans?

390
00:22:16,665 --> 00:22:19,732
♪ Lonely days are gone

391
00:22:19,833 --> 00:22:22,665
NARRATOR: Although Washington
planned to vastly increase

392
00:22:22,766 --> 00:22:25,633
military support of the
South Vietnamese Army,

393
00:22:25,732 --> 00:22:28,932
General Abrams knew that
Vietnamization alone

394
00:22:29,032 --> 00:22:31,333
could never defeat the enemy.

395
00:22:31,432 --> 00:22:33,865
But he had his orders.

396
00:22:33,965 --> 00:22:36,633
McPEAK: The reason I was ordered home early

397
00:22:36,732 --> 00:22:38,566
was because Nixon... President Nixon

398
00:22:38,665 --> 00:22:42,032
announced the policy of Vietnamization.

399
00:22:42,133 --> 00:22:46,232
Now, Vietnamization was a lie,

400
00:22:46,333 --> 00:22:50,200
but it had an element of truth in it.

401
00:22:50,299 --> 00:22:52,566
We were leaving, okay?

402
00:22:52,665 --> 00:22:54,566
And that sealed the South's fate.

403
00:22:54,665 --> 00:22:56,066
I knew it.

404
00:22:56,165 --> 00:22:59,099
And I think anybody who was conscious

405
00:22:59,200 --> 00:23:00,932
and could see what was going on

406
00:23:01,032 --> 00:23:02,232
knew it.

407
00:23:02,333 --> 00:23:04,833
NARRATOR: Nixon then flew to Midway Island

408
00:23:04,932 --> 00:23:08,500
to meet with South Vietnamese
President Nguyen Van Thieu.

409
00:23:08,599 --> 00:23:11,700
He had not dared invite Thieu to Washington

410
00:23:11,799 --> 00:23:14,700
for fear of sparking mass demonstrations.

411
00:23:14,799 --> 00:23:16,165
♪ Lonely days are gone

412
00:23:16,266 --> 00:23:18,365
President Thieu informed me

413
00:23:18,465 --> 00:23:22,266
that the progress of the training program

414
00:23:22,365 --> 00:23:23,965
and the equipping program

415
00:23:24,066 --> 00:23:26,266
for South Vietnamese forces

416
00:23:26,365 --> 00:23:31,400
had been so successful, uh,
that he could now recommend

417
00:23:31,500 --> 00:23:34,799
that the United States begin to replace

418
00:23:34,900 --> 00:23:39,200
U.S. combat forces with Vietnamese forces.

419
00:23:39,299 --> 00:23:41,932
(speaking Vietnamese)

420
00:23:44,500 --> 00:23:46,900
NARRATOR: Thieu had said no such thing

421
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:49,532
but felt he had to go along.

422
00:23:49,633 --> 00:23:52,333
"There is nothing I can
do," he told a friend.

423
00:23:52,432 --> 00:23:54,833
"Just as we could do nothing about it

424
00:23:54,932 --> 00:23:57,532
"when Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Johnson

425
00:23:57,633 --> 00:24:00,599
decided to come in."

426
00:24:00,700 --> 00:24:03,665
"We were clearly on the
way out of Vietnam,"

427
00:24:03,766 --> 00:24:06,900
National Security Advisor
Henry Kissinger remembered,

428
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:09,732
"by negotiation if possible,

429
00:24:09,833 --> 00:24:13,633
by unilateral withdrawal if necessary."

430
00:24:13,732 --> 00:24:16,665
He and the president were redefining

431
00:24:16,766 --> 00:24:19,633
what victory would look like.

432
00:24:19,732 --> 00:24:22,665
TOM VALLELY: Nixon and Kissinger...

433
00:24:22,766 --> 00:24:24,732
They...

434
00:24:24,833 --> 00:24:27,099
Their job is to clean up.

435
00:24:27,200 --> 00:24:28,799
They're, they're...

436
00:24:28,900 --> 00:24:30,833
The war's over, okay?

437
00:24:30,932 --> 00:24:34,400
When Nixon and Kissinger,
when they come, they're...

438
00:24:34,500 --> 00:24:35,865
they're not gonna win the war.

439
00:24:35,965 --> 00:24:38,299
("Taps" playing) So they develop

440
00:24:38,400 --> 00:24:40,066
a secret strategy.

441
00:24:40,165 --> 00:24:44,099
They surrender without
saying they surrendered.

442
00:24:46,566 --> 00:24:49,766
This is not a bad strategy,
this is the only strategy.

443
00:24:49,865 --> 00:24:53,700
("Circle for a Landing" by Three
Dog Night starts playing)

444
00:24:53,799 --> 00:24:56,266
(indistinct announcement over P.A.)

445
00:24:58,099 --> 00:25:01,633
NARRATOR: As American soldiers
began leaving South Vietnam,

446
00:25:01,732 --> 00:25:04,932
American weaponry and materiel poured in.

447
00:25:06,500 --> 00:25:08,599
♪ Circle for a landing

448
00:25:08,700 --> 00:25:10,900
♪ Get your feet back on the ground ♪

449
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:14,000
More than a million M16 rifles,

450
00:25:14,099 --> 00:25:20,032
40,000 grenade launchers,
thousands of wheeled vehicles...

451
00:25:20,133 --> 00:25:21,766
so many, one congressman complained,

452
00:25:21,865 --> 00:25:24,965
that it seemed as if the
United States taxpayer

453
00:25:25,066 --> 00:25:29,266
was being asked to "put every
South Vietnamese soldier

454
00:25:29,365 --> 00:25:31,766
behind the wheel."

455
00:25:31,865 --> 00:25:34,032
NEIL SHEEHAN: It didn't
make any sense, of course,

456
00:25:34,133 --> 00:25:37,032
because we tried that in 1962 and '63.

457
00:25:37,133 --> 00:25:38,932
The people hadn't changed.

458
00:25:39,032 --> 00:25:40,732
They were just giving 'em more furniture.

459
00:25:42,932 --> 00:25:45,932
NGUYEN THOI BUNG:

460
00:26:03,799 --> 00:26:07,633
NARRATOR: South Vietnamese
armed forces were expanded

461
00:26:07,732 --> 00:26:12,000
from 850,000 men to over a million.

462
00:26:12,099 --> 00:26:14,032
But nothing could alter the fact

463
00:26:14,133 --> 00:26:15,599
that rampant corruption

464
00:26:15,700 --> 00:26:19,133
continually eroded their effectiveness.

465
00:26:19,232 --> 00:26:21,333
DON WEBSTER: The way it works is this:

466
00:26:21,432 --> 00:26:23,799
a man makes a deal with
his commanding officer,

467
00:26:23,900 --> 00:26:26,532
perhaps to pay the officer his full salary.

468
00:26:26,633 --> 00:26:29,599
In exchange, you never
have to show up for duty,

469
00:26:29,700 --> 00:26:32,165
except perhaps once a week at the ceremony.

470
00:26:32,266 --> 00:26:34,299
So while you're theoretically in the Army,

471
00:26:34,400 --> 00:26:36,799
you can hold a full-time civilian job.

472
00:26:38,066 --> 00:26:41,000
LAM QUANG THI:

473
00:26:53,833 --> 00:26:56,900
(gunfire)

474
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:00,599
NARRATOR: Many ARVN units did fight well.

475
00:27:03,665 --> 00:27:05,700
They had borne the brunt of the fighting

476
00:27:05,799 --> 00:27:07,232
during the Tet Offensive,

477
00:27:07,333 --> 00:27:10,165
and, by the middle of 1969,

478
00:27:10,266 --> 00:27:14,865
90,000 of them had been killed in combat.

479
00:27:14,965 --> 00:27:20,365
Their bravery was often
overlooked by Americans.

480
00:27:20,465 --> 00:27:24,032
VALLELY: We were disdainful of them.

481
00:27:24,133 --> 00:27:27,099
We overstated their incompetence

482
00:27:27,200 --> 00:27:30,932
because we wanted to
overstate our importance.

483
00:27:31,032 --> 00:27:32,865
(booming in distance)

484
00:27:32,965 --> 00:27:36,099
(men shouting, gunfire)

485
00:27:42,965 --> 00:27:48,133
Part of going to war in
Vietnam I, I enjoyed.

486
00:27:48,232 --> 00:27:53,000
If you survive it, it's,
it's quite thrilling.

487
00:27:53,099 --> 00:27:56,066
It's the history of the world.

488
00:27:57,532 --> 00:27:58,932
It's hard to survive.

489
00:27:59,032 --> 00:28:00,965
I mean, in, where I was,
survival is an issue.

490
00:28:01,066 --> 00:28:05,165
I would have loved to have
been in the National Guard.

491
00:28:07,365 --> 00:28:08,665
Period.

492
00:28:08,766 --> 00:28:10,275
("Bad Moon Rising" by Creedence
Clearwater Revival playing)

493
00:28:10,299 --> 00:28:13,099
I knew the core issue

494
00:28:13,200 --> 00:28:16,032
of what was acceptable
in war and what wasn't.

495
00:28:16,133 --> 00:28:17,432
I knew that.

496
00:28:17,532 --> 00:28:20,299
I didn't need to get that
from the Marine Corps.

497
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:23,766
I got that from Sunday school.

498
00:28:23,865 --> 00:28:26,766
NARRATOR: Thomas John
Vallely was born in Boston,

499
00:28:26,865 --> 00:28:28,232
the son of a judge,

500
00:28:28,333 --> 00:28:31,200
and brought up in the suburb of Newton.

501
00:28:31,299 --> 00:28:36,700
Undiagnosed dyslexia kept him
from doing well in school.

502
00:28:36,799 --> 00:28:38,833
By 1969,

503
00:28:38,932 --> 00:28:42,599
Vallely was a radio operator
in the Marine Corps,

504
00:28:42,700 --> 00:28:45,732
part of a massive
search-and-destroy mission

505
00:28:45,833 --> 00:28:50,000
in Quang Nam Province in the
northern part of South Vietnam.

506
00:28:50,099 --> 00:28:51,700
(men shouting, gunfire)

507
00:28:51,799 --> 00:28:53,432
On August 13,

508
00:28:53,532 --> 00:28:55,299
his company was ambushed

509
00:28:55,400 --> 00:28:58,900
and came under heavy machine gun fire.

510
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:00,400
(gunfire)

511
00:29:06,299 --> 00:29:10,432
VALLELY: It was a "grab 'em by
the belt" type of situation.

512
00:29:10,532 --> 00:29:13,432
And we lost a lot of people.

513
00:29:14,965 --> 00:29:16,299
So did they.

514
00:29:18,133 --> 00:29:20,200
Lot of people laying around.

515
00:29:20,299 --> 00:29:22,732
(gunfire, explosion)

516
00:29:22,833 --> 00:29:25,099
NARRATOR: Vallely radioed
for reinforcements.

517
00:29:25,200 --> 00:29:28,732
Then he picked up a rifle and ammunition

518
00:29:28,833 --> 00:29:31,232
from a wounded Marine,

519
00:29:31,333 --> 00:29:33,365
and, firing as he went, took up a position

520
00:29:33,465 --> 00:29:36,299
just ten feet from an enemy machine gun.

521
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:41,900
He hurled a smoke grenade
to mark their position.

522
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:45,900
And then, as enemy fire
swept back and forth

523
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:48,165
across the field,

524
00:29:48,266 --> 00:29:49,833
he moved from Marine to Marine,

525
00:29:49,932 --> 00:29:51,566
pointing out targets among the trees

526
00:29:51,665 --> 00:29:54,432
and encouraging his comrades.

527
00:30:00,432 --> 00:30:03,333
For his conspicuous gallantry,

528
00:30:03,432 --> 00:30:07,200
Tom Vallely was awarded the Silver Star.

529
00:30:07,299 --> 00:30:09,532
VALLELY: You want to
