602
00:34:09,032 --> 00:34:10,865
the hair gonna be motherfucking two inches.

603
00:34:10,965 --> 00:34:12,599
And why we got to get our hair cut?

604
00:34:12,699 --> 00:34:14,099
That's what I want to know.

605
00:34:14,199 --> 00:34:16,099
♪ Yeah, man, ooh, yeah

606
00:34:16,199 --> 00:34:19,065
WAYNE SMITH: Vietnam was a microcosm.

607
00:34:19,166 --> 00:34:20,932
Everything that was happening in America

608
00:34:21,032 --> 00:34:22,800
was happening in Vietnam, really,

609
00:34:22,900 --> 00:34:24,965
in one way, shape, or form.

610
00:34:25,065 --> 00:34:26,900
In the rear,

611
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:30,500
there were Confederate flags flying.

612
00:34:30,599 --> 00:34:33,666
SOLDIER 2: I mean, of all
things to have over here, man,

613
00:34:33,766 --> 00:34:36,000
why a Confederate flag?

614
00:34:36,099 --> 00:34:38,266
As a matter of fact, I
think there ought to be

615
00:34:38,365 --> 00:34:42,333
some goddamn law to fucking
outlaw them goddamn flags, man.

616
00:34:42,432 --> 00:34:46,565
The fucking Confederacy is gone, man.

617
00:34:46,666 --> 00:34:49,065
SMITH: When one is in an environment

618
00:34:49,166 --> 00:34:53,800
where everyone has a gun, automatic weapon,

619
00:34:53,900 --> 00:34:56,599
I'll be goddamned if someone's
gonna call me a nigger

620
00:34:56,699 --> 00:34:58,666
or give me a bullshit order.

621
00:34:58,766 --> 00:35:02,666
I mean, that was the attitude,
to risk my life for what?

622
00:35:02,766 --> 00:35:04,199
REDDING: ♪ Sweeter than honey

623
00:35:04,300 --> 00:35:07,199
ROGER HARRIS: There was all
kind of craziness happening,

624
00:35:07,300 --> 00:35:10,532
because white people were still
calling, you know, us niggers,

625
00:35:10,632 --> 00:35:13,532
and then there were some black
people calling us Uncle Toms.

626
00:35:13,632 --> 00:35:15,065
There were the antiwar folks

627
00:35:15,166 --> 00:35:17,400
who were calling us baby killers, say...

628
00:35:17,500 --> 00:35:19,476
You know, you can say what
you want, but you can say it

629
00:35:19,500 --> 00:35:21,209
from over there because
if you get in range,

630
00:35:21,233 --> 00:35:25,032
you're gonna get serious
damage done to you.

631
00:35:25,132 --> 00:35:26,699
Say what you want from a distance,

632
00:35:26,800 --> 00:35:28,941
but if you get close to me, I'm
gonna rip your throat out.

633
00:35:28,965 --> 00:35:30,532
You know?

634
00:35:30,632 --> 00:35:34,199
JUAN RAMIREZ: But when we
walked outside that wire,

635
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:37,233
we went out into the bush, we were tight.

636
00:35:37,333 --> 00:35:39,565
Even with our differences.

637
00:35:39,666 --> 00:35:41,733
Maybe we had threatened each other,

638
00:35:41,833 --> 00:35:44,900
we'd had a fight back in the base,

639
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:47,666
but when we were out there, you know,

640
00:35:47,766 --> 00:35:51,333
we, we were a, a fighting unit.

641
00:35:52,800 --> 00:35:56,699
And it's almost like an identity crisis.

642
00:35:56,800 --> 00:36:00,800
I was born here, and my
parents were born here.

643
00:36:00,900 --> 00:36:03,132
I felt, in a way,

644
00:36:03,233 --> 00:36:06,300
more American than Mexican.

645
00:36:06,400 --> 00:36:07,965
MAN: ...hand and repeat after me...

646
00:36:08,065 --> 00:36:12,365
NARRATOR: The U.S. military did
not officially count Hispanics,

647
00:36:12,465 --> 00:36:17,099
but an estimated 170,000
would serve in Vietnam

648
00:36:17,199 --> 00:36:21,233
and more than 3,000 lost their lives.

649
00:36:21,333 --> 00:36:23,900
Like their fathers and grandfathers,

650
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:28,032
many saw military service
as both a patriotic duty

651
00:36:28,132 --> 00:36:30,900
and an opportunity to
advance their standing

652
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:33,500
in the United States.

653
00:36:33,599 --> 00:36:36,699
But as casualties mounted

654
00:36:36,800 --> 00:36:38,833
and with a burgeoning
Chicano identity movement

655
00:36:38,932 --> 00:36:41,365
among farm workers and college students,

656
00:36:41,465 --> 00:36:46,132
anti-war sentiment in
Hispanic communities grew.

657
00:36:46,233 --> 00:36:49,865
We're protesting against the
discriminatory draft laws

658
00:36:49,965 --> 00:36:52,032
that give deferments

659
00:36:52,132 --> 00:36:55,365
to all the Anglo middle-class
people of this country

660
00:36:55,465 --> 00:36:58,465
and make the heaviest burdens of the war

661
00:36:58,565 --> 00:37:01,632
fall on the poor, fall on theMexicano.

662
00:37:01,733 --> 00:37:04,000
RAMIREZ: I had learned

663
00:37:04,099 --> 00:37:08,000
about my sister and my
mother's antiwar activities

664
00:37:08,099 --> 00:37:10,000
while I was still in Vietnam.

665
00:37:10,099 --> 00:37:12,266
In fact, my sister wrote and said,

666
00:37:12,365 --> 00:37:14,800
"I hope you're okay with this."

667
00:37:14,900 --> 00:37:16,532
And she was honest with me.

668
00:37:16,632 --> 00:37:18,532
She told me what they were doing.

669
00:37:18,632 --> 00:37:21,766
She says, "I'm doing it for you,
'cause I want you to come home."

670
00:37:21,865 --> 00:37:23,699
(indistinct chanting)

671
00:37:28,932 --> 00:37:30,000
(TV clicks on)

672
00:37:30,099 --> 00:37:33,333
In line with our policy of taking a stand

673
00:37:33,432 --> 00:37:35,166
on the pressing issues of the day,

674
00:37:35,266 --> 00:37:38,166
we now present another in our
continuing series of editorials.

675
00:37:38,266 --> 00:37:39,132
The subject:

676
00:37:39,233 --> 00:37:42,132
are our draft laws unfair?

677
00:37:42,233 --> 00:37:44,300
Here again, speaking for our program,

678
00:37:44,400 --> 00:37:46,965
is Mr. Patrick Paulsen, vice president.

679
00:37:47,065 --> 00:37:48,699
(applause)

680
00:37:48,800 --> 00:37:51,099
Now, we don't claim the draft is perfect,

681
00:37:51,199 --> 00:37:53,266
and we do have a constructive proposal

682
00:37:53,365 --> 00:37:55,465
for a workable alternative.

683
00:37:55,565 --> 00:37:57,599
We propose a draft lottery

684
00:37:57,699 --> 00:38:00,065
in which the names of all eligible males

685
00:38:00,166 --> 00:38:01,733
will be put into a hat,

686
00:38:01,833 --> 00:38:05,400
and the men will be drafted
according to their head sizes.

687
00:38:05,500 --> 00:38:09,032
The tiny heads will go
into the military service

688
00:38:09,132 --> 00:38:13,465
and the fat heads will go into government.

689
00:38:13,565 --> 00:38:15,465
SOLDIER (on radio):
Roger, 3-1 is on his way.

690
00:38:15,565 --> 00:38:18,199
SOLDIER (over radio): 5-8-1.

691
00:38:18,300 --> 00:38:22,333
VINCENT OKAMOTO: A 19-year-old
high school dropout says,

692
00:38:22,432 --> 00:38:25,199
"Why are we here?"

693
00:38:25,300 --> 00:38:27,065
And the, the standard response,

694
00:38:27,166 --> 00:38:29,099
at least on an official level, was,

695
00:38:29,199 --> 00:38:32,065
to prevent international communism

696
00:38:32,166 --> 00:38:35,065
from conquering the world.

697
00:38:35,166 --> 00:38:38,965
The men say, "Hey, that, that's bullshit."

698
00:38:41,266 --> 00:38:42,800
So the other reason put forth,

699
00:38:42,900 --> 00:38:44,932
at least in the latter days of the war,

700
00:38:45,032 --> 00:38:47,400
was to maintain America's
international credibility

701
00:38:47,500 --> 00:38:50,065
with our allies, and our enemies.

702
00:38:50,166 --> 00:38:54,300
Uh, no 19, 20-year-old kid
wants to die to maintain

703
00:38:54,400 --> 00:38:57,599
the credibility of Lyndon
Johnson or Richard Nixon.

704
00:38:57,699 --> 00:39:01,099
And so, within a relatively short time,

705
00:39:01,199 --> 00:39:03,333
the guys were saying,

706
00:39:03,432 --> 00:39:06,199
"Look, we shouldn't be here, but we are.

707
00:39:06,300 --> 00:39:08,199
"So my only function in life

708
00:39:08,300 --> 00:39:11,465
"is to try and keep you alive, buddy,

709
00:39:11,565 --> 00:39:14,632
"and to keep my precious
ass from being killed.

710
00:39:14,733 --> 00:39:18,400
And then to go home and forget about this."

711
00:39:20,833 --> 00:39:23,432
SOLDIER: The grunts, uh,

712
00:39:23,532 --> 00:39:26,666
don't always do what the
captain says, you know.

713
00:39:26,766 --> 00:39:30,233
We got, uh... the captain will stay back,

714
00:39:30,333 --> 00:39:32,233
he'll tell the platoon or something

715
00:39:32,333 --> 00:39:35,032
to go out so many hundred meters, you know.

716
00:39:35,132 --> 00:39:36,865
We don't do it.

717
00:39:36,965 --> 00:39:38,766
We only go as far as we get out of sight,

718
00:39:38,865 --> 00:39:40,300
sit down, and come back in.

719
00:39:40,400 --> 00:39:42,309
JOHN PILGER: What happens
to an unpopular officer

720
00:39:42,333 --> 00:39:44,365
out in the field?

721
00:39:44,465 --> 00:39:47,400
Mostly unpopular officers,
from what I've heard,

722
00:39:47,500 --> 00:39:50,132
if they, if they mess
with a grunt too much,

723
00:39:50,233 --> 00:39:53,099
they get shot at.

724
00:39:53,199 --> 00:39:56,599
NARRATOR: It had always been a part of war.

725
00:39:56,699 --> 00:39:59,733
In Vietnam, it was called "fragging,"

726
00:39:59,833 --> 00:40:04,065
after the fragmentation
grenades most often used.

727
00:40:04,166 --> 00:40:09,233
Beginning in the summer of 1969,

728
00:40:09,333 --> 00:40:13,199
as thousands of American
troops began going home,

729
00:40:13,300 --> 00:40:16,865
the number of reports of the
murder or attempted murder

730
00:40:16,965 --> 00:40:19,000
by enlisted men of their superiors

731
00:40:19,099 --> 00:40:22,132
increased alarmingly.

732
00:40:22,233 --> 00:40:27,266
The Army would investigate
nearly 800 cases.

733
00:40:27,365 --> 00:40:29,333
Most took place far from the fighting,

734
00:40:29,432 --> 00:40:32,132
usually the violent outcome
of arguments over race

735
00:40:32,233 --> 00:40:34,400
or women or drugs

736
00:40:34,500 --> 00:40:37,500
rather than the war itself.

737
00:40:37,599 --> 00:40:40,166
But there were exceptions.

738
00:40:40,266 --> 00:40:42,233
OKAMOTO: It's a totally different army

739
00:40:42,333 --> 00:40:46,166
than what we sent to Vietnam in 1965.

740
00:40:46,266 --> 00:40:50,300
And the new lieutenant comes in,
all gung-ho for body count.

741
00:40:50,400 --> 00:40:53,932
He wants contact, he goes crazy, and says,

742
00:40:54,032 --> 00:40:56,333
"I want a volunteer for this."

743
00:40:56,432 --> 00:40:59,032
(rapid gunfire)

744
00:40:59,132 --> 00:41:04,865
That new gung-ho officer was
a clear and present danger

745
00:41:04,965 --> 00:41:08,666
to the life and limb of the grunts.

746
00:41:08,766 --> 00:41:11,333
They'd have subtle hints,
like a little note saying,

747
00:41:11,432 --> 00:41:14,065
"We're gonna kill your ass
if you keep this up."

748
00:41:14,166 --> 00:41:17,132
Or instead of a fragmentation grenade,

749
00:41:17,233 --> 00:41:20,965
they may throw a smoke grenade
in an officer's hooch or bunker.

750
00:41:21,065 --> 00:41:25,032
And if they didn't correct
their behavior and outlook,

751
00:41:25,132 --> 00:41:28,532
yeah, they would frag them.

752
00:41:28,632 --> 00:41:32,300
I saw it happen in a very, uh, strange way.

753
00:41:32,400 --> 00:41:40,400
We were in a base and a Marine
started running towards me.

754
00:41:40,599 --> 00:41:42,666
I didn't realize that what he...

755
00:41:42,766 --> 00:41:44,900
what he was doing back
in the dark over there

756
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:47,166
was actually throw a hand grenade

757
00:41:47,266 --> 00:41:50,733
underneath the space that
is underneath a hooch.

758
00:41:50,833 --> 00:41:52,132
(explosion)

759
00:41:52,233 --> 00:41:54,599
And when it exploded, I went, "Holy shit."

760
00:41:54,699 --> 00:41:58,032
And I knew right away what he had done.

761
00:41:58,132 --> 00:42:01,400
And he was an African-American Marine.

762
00:42:01,500 --> 00:42:03,400
African-Americans were treated

763
00:42:03,500 --> 00:42:05,865
with disrespect by their superiors.

764
00:42:05,965 --> 00:42:09,800
This was not uncommon.

765
00:42:09,900 --> 00:42:14,800
So in a ways, as bad as this sounds,

766
00:42:14,900 --> 00:42:17,300
maybe that guy had it coming to him.

767
00:42:17,400 --> 00:42:18,865
I don't know.

768
00:42:22,099 --> 00:42:24,865
In Paris, the 29th session
of the so-called peace talks

769
00:42:24,965 --> 00:42:25,865
took place.

770
00:42:25,965 --> 00:42:27,766
There was no progress.

771
00:42:27,865 --> 00:42:31,199
In Vietnam, it was announced
that 139 Americans

772
00:42:31,300 --> 00:42:32,800
lost their lives last week,

773
00:42:32,900 --> 00:42:35,500
bringing total deaths in our longest war...

774
00:42:35,599 --> 00:42:38,500
NARRATOR: The four-way peace talks in Paris

775
00:42:38,599 --> 00:42:41,166
continued to go nowhere.

776
00:42:41,266 --> 00:42:44,900
To break the logjam, Nixon
directed Henry Kissinger

777
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:47,666
to begin secret talks,

778
00:42:47,766 --> 00:42:50,400
the first in a series
of clandestine meetings

779
00:42:50,500 --> 00:42:53,266
with the North Vietnamese alone.

780
00:42:53,365 --> 00:42:55,666
They first met in an apartment building

781
00:42:55,766 --> 00:42:57,800
on the Rue de Rivoli.

782
00:42:57,900 --> 00:43:00,833
The Viet Cong and the South
Vietnamese government

783
00:43:00,932 --> 00:43:03,632
were not included.

784
00:43:03,733 --> 00:43:06,666
Hanoi remained immovable.

785
00:43:06,766 --> 00:43:10,532
They would not even admit they
had troops in South Vietnam,

786
00:43:10,632 --> 00:43:14,532
let alone discuss withdrawing them.

787
00:43:14,632 --> 00:43:16,400
Now Kissinger warned

788
00:43:16,500 --> 00:43:19,699
that if there were no change in
their position by November 1,

789
00:43:19,800 --> 00:43:21,733
the one-year anniversary

790
00:43:21,833 --> 00:43:24,166
of President Johnson's bombing halt,

791
00:43:24,266 --> 00:43:25,900
President Nixon

792
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:28,900
would "consider steps
of grave consequence."

793
00:43:41,500 --> 00:43:45,000
September 2, 1969,

794
00:43:45,099 --> 00:43:47,333
was the 24th anniversary

795
00:43:47,432 --> 00:43:51,233
of Ho Chi Minh's declaration
of Vietnamese independence

796
00:43:51,333 --> 00:43:53,766
in Hanoi's Ba Dinh Square.

797
00:43:55,766 --> 00:44:00,565
At 9:45 that morning, Ho died.

798
00:44:00,666 --> 00:44:05,300
He was said to be 79, but
like so much about him,

799
00:44:05,400 --> 00:44:10,699
the precise date of his birth
was shrouded in mystery.

800
00:44:10,800 --> 00:44:13,400
He had been "Uncle Ho" for decades,

801
00:44:13,500 --> 00:44:16,800
the living embodiment of the
struggle against the Japanese,

802
00:44:16,900 --> 00:44:19,800
the French, the Saigon government,

803
00:44:19,900 --> 00:44:22,733
and then the Americans.

804
00:44:22,833 --> 00:44:24,766
♪

805
00:44:24,865 --> 00:44:27,632
In a speech to the National Assembly,

806
00:44:27,733 --> 00:44:32,166
Le Duan, the First Secretary
of the Communist Party,

807
00:44:32,266 --> 00:44:33,565
who had been the architect

808
00:44:33,666 --> 00:44:36,233
of North Vietnamese military policy

809
00:44:36,333 --> 00:44:37,599
for a decade,

810
00:44:37,699 --> 00:44:41,766
promised to fulfill what
he said was Ho's vision:

811
00:44:41,865 --> 00:44:47,733
the reunification of the
country on communist terms.

812
00:44:49,300 --> 00:44:51,965
Nothing had changed.

813
00:44:52,065 --> 00:44:53,908
ROBERT FRISHMAN: Hanoi has
given the false impression

814
00:44:53,932 --> 00:44:57,233
that all is wine and roses and it isn't so.

815
00:44:57,333 --> 00:44:59,699
NARRATOR: The same day Ho Chi Minh died,

816
00:44:59,800 --> 00:45:02,365
an unusual press conference was held

817
00:45:02,465 --> 00:45:05,365
at the Bethesda Naval Medical Center.

818
00:45:05,465 --> 00:45:08,132
Two ailing prisoners of war,

819
00:45:08,233 --> 00:45:11,699
Robert Frishman and Douglas Hegdahl,

820
00:45:11,800 --> 00:45:14,065
who had recently been released
by the North Vietnamese,

821
00:45:14,166 --> 00:45:16,300
spoke in public for the first time

822
00:45:16,400 --> 00:45:18,199
about the severe treatment

823
00:45:18,300 --> 00:45:21,666
they and their fellow
prisoners had received.

824
00:45:21,766 --> 00:45:24,233
I don't think solitary confinement,

825
00:45:24,333 --> 00:45:28,032
forced statements, living
in a cage for three years,

826
00:45:28,132 --> 00:45:31,965
being put in straps, not being
allowed to sleep or eat,

827
00:45:32,065 --> 00:45:35,532
removal of fingernails,
being hung from a ceiling,

828
00:45:35,632 --> 00:45:37,900
having an infected arm
which was almost lost,

829
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:40,233
not receiving medical care,

830
00:45:40,333 --> 00:45:42,565
being dragged along the
ground with a broken leg,

831
00:45:42,666 --> 00:45:45,599
or not allowing exchange of
mail to prisoners of war

832
00:45:45,699 --> 00:45:47,032
are humane.

833
00:45:47,132 --> 00:45:51,333
NARRATOR: Douglas Hegdahl
was quiet, self-effacing,

834
00:45:51,432 --> 00:45:54,065
and so apparently clueless,

835
00:45:54,166 --> 00:45:56,233
his North Vietnamese guards

836
00:45:56,333 --> 00:45:59,065
had called him the "stupid one."

837
00:45:59,166 --> 00:46:00,632
But once released,

838
00:46:00,733 --> 00:46:03,900
he was a gold mine of information.

839
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:07,900
He had memorized the names
of more than 200 prisoners

840
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:11,632
to the tune of "Old McDonald Had a Farm."

841
00:46:11,733 --> 00:46:14,565
Thanks to him, scores of American families

842
00:46:14,666 --> 00:46:16,766
would find out for the first time

843
00:46:16,865 --> 00:46:22,032
that their sons and husbands
and fathers were still alive.

844
00:46:22,132 --> 00:46:25,565
Within a few days of the press conference,

845
00:46:25,666 --> 00:46:29,432
Hanoi's treatment of the
prisoners began to improve.

846
00:46:29,532 --> 00:46:33,400
"A lot less brutality,"
one captive remembered,

847
00:46:33,500 --> 00:46:36,032
"and larger bowls of rice."

848
00:46:38,632 --> 00:46:40,800
(explosion)

849
00:46:40,900 --> 00:46:42,465
(men yelling)

850
00:46:42,565 --> 00:46:44,465
(rapid gunfire)

851
00:46:50,833 --> 00:46:52,242
DEVALLIER: All right, who's wounded?

852
00:46:52,266 --> 00:46:54,965
All right, give me some cover!

853
00:46:55,065 --> 00:46:57,733
RICHARD THRELKELD: Devallier is
the lone medic in the platoon.

854
00:46:57,833 --> 00:46:59,000
He's scared,

855
00:46:59,099 --> 00:47:01,432
scared from the moment he
gets out of the chopper

856
00:47:01,532 --> 00:47:02,965
to the moment it picks him up.

857
00:47:03,065 --> 00:47:05,965
Scared that someday he's
going to get killed

858
00:47:06,065 --> 00:47:09,032
picking up a wounded buddy.

859
00:47:09,132 --> 00:47:11,032
(rapid gunfire, men yelling)

860
00:47:12,766 --> 00:47:14,965
WAYNE SMITH: I was the replacement

861
00:47:15,065 --> 00:47:18,666
for a medic who had been killed.

862
00:47:18,766 --> 00:47:22,333
First time out, we were
assigned to do a patrol.

863
00:47:22,432 --> 00:47:25,766
MAN: Remember to stop the bleeding!

864
00:47:25,865 --> 00:47:31,465
SMITH: And we stumbled
actually into an ambush.

865
00:47:31,565 --> 00:47:34,199
(explosion)

866
00:47:34,300 --> 00:47:37,666
And it was incredibly terrifying.

867
00:47:37,766 --> 00:47:40,065
Guys were screaming and yelling.

868
00:47:40,166 --> 00:47:42,465
There was shooting everywhere.

869
00:47:42,565 --> 00:47:46,532
That first firefight, I
remember praying to God,

870
00:47:46,632 --> 00:47:52,766
if He got me through this that
I would make a difference.

871
00:47:52,865 --> 00:47:57,233
That I really would make a difference.

872
00:47:57,333 --> 00:48:00,400
MEDIC: Sometimes their lives
depend on you, I mean;

873
00:48:00,500 --> 00:48:03,432
you hold it in your hands, as a medic.

874
00:48:03,532 --> 00:48:06,400
It's just hard to say but right then,

875
00:48:06,500 --> 00:48:08,733
you hold life and death in your hand.

876
00:48:08,833 --> 00:48:12,532
NARRATOR: In Vietnam,
medics and navy corpsmen

877
00:48:12,632 --> 00:48:15,065
accompanied infantry units on patrols,

878
00:48:15,166 --> 00:48:17,032
search and destroy missions,

879
00:48:17,132 --> 00:48:20,632
and large-scale combat operations.

880
00:48:20,733 --> 00:48:24,500
Nearly 2,000 would lose their lives.

881
00:48:24,599 --> 00:48:26,432
(helicopter whirring)

882
00:48:28,199 --> 00:48:30,766
Unlike in previous wars,

883
00:48:30,865 --> 00:48:34,166
many medics in Vietnam
chose to carry weapons,

884
00:48:34,266 --> 00:48:36,666
and when the shooting started,

885
00:48:36,766 --> 00:48:39,465
were willing to use them
to protect themselves

886
00:48:39,565 --> 00:48:42,500
and their wounded comrades.

887
00:48:42,599 --> 00:48:46,000
SMITH: I carried an M16,

888
00:48:46,099 --> 00:48:49,132
but I did not know if I could kill.

889
00:48:49,233 --> 00:48:52,833
Part of being a medic was to save lives.

890
00:48:52,932 --> 00:48:59,233
I wondered, if the scenario
presented itself, would I?

891
00:48:59,333 --> 00:49:03,965
I did participate in shooting at the enemy.

892
00:49:04,065 --> 00:49:06,500
We killed a lot of people.

893
00:49:06,599 --> 00:49:09,865
I feel that responsibility.

894
00:49:11,300 --> 00:49:14,166
I feel blood on my hands.

895
00:49:19,532 --> 00:49:24,132
When you kill someone for your country,

896
00:49:24,233 --> 00:49:27,099
all things change.

897
00:49:28,733 --> 00:49:30,099
("Come Ye" by Nina Simone playing)

898
00:49:30,199 --> 00:49:32,632
♪ Come ye

899
00:49:35,032 --> 00:49:38,432
♪ Ye who would have peace...

900
00:49:38,532 --> 00:49:39,972
SAM BROWN: We believed it's possible

901
00:49:40,032 --> 00:49:42,166
to create a substantial
majority in this country

902
00:49:42,266 --> 00:49:43,865
for withdrawal from Vietnam,

903
00:49:43,965 --> 00:49:45,733
and that's what we're
about in the long run.

904
00:49:45,833 --> 00:49:47,699
In November, we'll be back again,

905
00:49:47,800 --> 00:49:49,300
in December, we'll be back again.

906
00:49:49,400 --> 00:49:51,266
And we intend to build the movement,

907
00:49:51,365 --> 00:49:53,666
which will make it imperative

908
00:49:53,766 --> 00:49:56,032
that the United States
withdraw from Vietnam.

909
00:49:56,132 --> 00:49:59,000
REPORTER: The organizers of
the moratorium do not aim

910
00:49:59,099 --> 00:50:01,733
at confrontation or
scuffles with the police.

911
00:50:01,833 --> 00:50:04,800
Instead, they want to involve
the most people possible

912
00:50:04,900 --> 00:50:07,833
in some gesture of protest, however modest,

913
00:50:07,932 --> 00:50:11,465
so as to show the administration
that a large bloc of Americans

914
00:50:11,565 --> 00:50:14,065
care not about winning or losing the war,

915
00:50:14,166 --> 00:50:16,365
but only about ending it.

916
00:50:16,465 --> 00:50:19,699
♪ Ye who have no fear

917
00:50:19,800 --> 00:50:20,965
Thank you.

918
00:50:21,065 --> 00:50:23,300
NIXON: Now, I understand

919
00:50:23,400 --> 00:50:25,599
that there has been and continues to be

920
00:50:25,699 --> 00:50:28,532
opposition to the war in
Vietnam on the campuses

921
00:50:28,632 --> 00:50:31,532
and also in the nation.

922
00:50:31,632 --> 00:50:32,666
Uh, we expect it.

923
00:50:32,766 --> 00:50:34,666
However, under no circumstances

924
00:50:34,766 --> 00:50:37,932
will I be affected whatever by it.

925
00:50:38,032 --> 00:50:41,932
NARRATOR: Hoping to undercut
support for the moratorium,

926
00:50:42,032 --> 00:50:44,233
Nixon canceled the draft calls

927
00:50:44,333 --> 00:50:48,099
for the months of November
and December 1969.

928
00:50:48,199 --> 00:50:51,500
And he instituted a random lottery system

929
00:50:51,599 --> 00:50:54,432
based on the date of a young man's birth,

930
00:50:54,532 --> 00:50:57,432
intended to treat rich and poor alike

931
00:50:57,532 --> 00:51:01,199
and do away with unfair deferments.

932
00:51:01,300 --> 00:51:04,800
It was good policy and a
brilliant political maneuver.

933
00:51:04,900 --> 00:51:06,199
(siren wails)

934
00:51:06,300 --> 00:51:07,666
On the line, brothers and sisters.

935
00:51:07,766 --> 00:51:09,166
On the line now.

936
00:51:09,266 --> 00:51:10,908
("Subterranean Homesick
Blues" by Bob Dylan playing)

937
00:51:10,932 --> 00:51:13,065
NARRATOR: As people across
the country organized

938
00:51:13,166 --> 00:51:15,000
for the peaceful moratorium,

939
00:51:15,099 --> 00:51:17,065
members of a radical faction

940
00:51:17,166 --> 00:51:19,900
of the Students for a Democratic Society...

941
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:21,199
the "Weathermen"...

942
00:51:21,300 --> 00:51:22,400
took more direct action.

943
00:51:22,500 --> 00:51:23,800
♪ The man in a trench coat

944
00:51:23,900 --> 00:51:26,500
NARRATOR: Less interested in ending the war

945
00:51:26,599 --> 00:51:29,099
than in sparking a violent revolution,

946
00:51:29,199 --> 00:51:33,932
they staged what they called
four "Days of Rage" in Chicago.

947
00:51:34,032 --> 00:51:36,099
DYLAN: ♪ You better duck
down the alleyway ♪

948
00:51:36,199 --> 00:51:39,266
MAN: We no longer simply resist the pigs.

949
00:51:39,365 --> 00:51:41,333
We no longer trap ourselves

950
00:51:41,432 --> 00:51:42,965
so that the only possible motion

951
00:51:43,065 --> 00:51:45,132
is in response to pig attacks.

952
00:51:45,233 --> 00:51:47,465
We have gone on the offensive.

953
00:51:47,565 --> 00:51:49,465
It is we who call the shots now.

954
00:51:49,565 --> 00:51:51,733
NARRATOR: "Kill all the rich people,"

955
00:51:51,833 --> 00:51:53,065
one of their leaders said.

956
00:51:53,166 --> 00:51:56,199
"Break up their cars and apartments.

957
00:51:56,300 --> 00:51:58,432
"Bring the revolution home.

958
00:51:58,532 --> 00:52:00,065
"Kill your parents.

959
00:52:00,166 --> 00:52:03,333
That's really where it's at."

960
00:52:03,432 --> 00:52:05,333
MAN: Weathermen takes its name from a line

961
00:52:05,432 --> 00:52:07,099
in a Bob Dylan song which says,

962
00:52:07,199 --> 00:52:08,932
"You don't need a weatherman

963
00:52:09,032 --> 00:52:10,465
to know the way the wind blows."

964
00:52:10,565 --> 00:52:12,099
DYLAN: ♪ Wash the plain clothes

965
00:52:12,199 --> 00:52:13,599
♪ You don't need a weatherman

966
00:52:13,699 --> 00:52:17,333
♪ To know which way the wind blows ♪

967
00:52:17,432 --> 00:52:19,733
NARRATOR: The Weathermen assumed

968
00:52:19,833 --> 00:52:22,500
thousands would rally to their cause.

969
00:52:22,599 --> 00:52:25,565
Only 600 did.

970
00:52:25,666 --> 00:52:29,166
They blew up a statue
honoring slain policemen,

971
00:52:29,266 --> 00:52:32,500
ran through the streets
wielding chains and pipes,

972
00:52:32,599 --> 00:52:34,733
smashing windows and windshields

973
00:52:34,833 --> 00:52:38,365
and charging police barriers.

974
00:52:38,465 --> 00:52:40,132
Six were shot.

975
00:52:40,233 --> 00:52:43,032
250 were jailed.

976
00:52:43,132 --> 00:52:46,365
75 policemen were injured;

977
00:52:46,465 --> 00:52:49,532
a city attorney was paralyzed for life.

978
00:52:49,632 --> 00:52:51,599
(siren wails)

979
00:52:51,699 --> 00:52:55,166
The Black Panthers denounced the Weathermen

980
00:52:55,266 --> 00:52:58,266
as "anarchistic, opportunistic...

981
00:52:58,365 --> 00:53:01,865
Custeristic."

982
00:53:01,965 --> 00:53:05,032
BILL ZIMMERMAN: Probably 1969 was the year

983
00:53:05,132 --> 00:53:07,300
in which most of us were more alienated

984
00:53:07,400 --> 00:53:11,233
and felt more like revolutionaries.

985
00:53:11,333 --> 00:53:16,000
And it led to a lot of crazy responses.

986
00:53:16,099 --> 00:53:19,965
I wanted the country to undergo
a radical transformation,

987
00:53:20,065 --> 00:53:22,965
a redistribution of wealth and power.

988
00:53:23,065 --> 00:53:25,266
But to try to bring that about

989
00:53:25,365 --> 00:53:28,099
through armed struggle in the United States

990
00:53:28,199 --> 00:53:30,166
was insane.

991
00:53:30,266 --> 00:53:32,632
These were all infantile fantasies

992
00:53:32,733 --> 00:53:35,532
that people came to out of the frustration

993
00:53:35,632 --> 00:53:38,266
of not having a workable strategy

994
00:53:38,365 --> 00:53:41,699
for ending the war.

995
00:53:41,800 --> 00:53:43,376
REPORTER: What do you think
people ought to do, governor,

996
00:53:43,400 --> 00:53:45,233
who are genuinely opposed to the war

997
00:53:45,333 --> 00:53:47,500
but not in favor of the Viet Cong?

998
00:53:47,599 --> 00:53:51,932
Well, I think that we have had...
experiences before

999
00:53:52,032 --> 00:53:54,599
of people who have been opposed to wars,

1000
00:53:54,699 --> 00:53:57,565
and I think they deal through
their own representatives,

1001
00:53:57,666 --> 00:54:00,065
and it's dealt with in government channels.

1002
00:54:00,166 --> 00:54:02,599
But once the killing starts,

1003
00:54:02,699 --> 00:54:04,565
the very difficult thing then is,

1004
00:54:04,666 --> 00:54:08,500
how do you register these protests

1005
00:54:08,599 --> 00:54:10,565
without lending comfort
and aid to the enemy,

1006
00:54:10,666 --> 00:54:12,565
without strengthening his resistance

1007
00:54:12,666 --> 00:54:13,766
and his will to fight

1008
00:54:13,865 --> 00:54:16,400
and thus killing more of our men?

1009
00:54:16,500 --> 00:54:20,599
And most Americans in the past
have always respected it.

1010
00:54:20,699 --> 00:54:22,233
You see, the people in this country

1011
00:54:22,333 --> 00:54:24,300
aren't fighting a Vietnam War.

1012
00:54:24,400 --> 00:54:25,800
The government's fighting it.

1013
00:54:25,900 --> 00:54:27,020
Well, the government is, uh,

1014
00:54:27,099 --> 00:54:29,233
the government is the
people, supposedly, No.

1015
00:54:29,333 --> 00:54:31,533
but in this instance, it is not.
Not anymore, it's not.

1016
00:54:31,599 --> 00:54:33,032
No, I agree with you, it is not.

1017
00:54:33,132 --> 00:54:34,465
Not in this situation, it's not.

1018
00:54:34,565 --> 00:54:36,000
Shouldn't I let my government know

1019
00:54:36,099 --> 00:54:37,233
that I think they're crazy?

1020
00:54:37,333 --> 00:54:38,800
I think they are insane, really.

1021
00:54:38,900 --> 00:54:40,932
This is an insane thing we're doing.

1022
00:54:41,032 --> 00:54:42,500
As a matter of fact,

1023
00:54:42,599 --> 00:54:44,666
Nixon said he will not listen to us

1024
00:54:44,766 --> 00:54:46,365
and that he will not be dictated to

1025
00:54:46,465 --> 00:54:48,266
from the people in the streets.

1026
00:54:48,365 --> 00:54:52,199
The people in the streets are me.

1027
00:54:52,300 --> 00:54:55,233
(chanting "peace now")

1028
00:54:55,333 --> 00:54:59,599
NARRATOR: The moratorium on October 15,

1029
00:54:59,699 --> 00:55:01,199
held all across the country,

1030
00:55:01,300 --> 00:55:04,132
was the largest outpouring
of public dissent

1031
00:55:04,233 --> 00:55:05,666
in American history.

1032
00:55:05,766 --> 00:55:09,632
("Blackbird" by the Beatles playing)

1033
00:55:09,733 --> 00:55:14,432
♪ Blackbird singing in
the dead of night ♪

1034
00:55:14,532 --> 00:55:19,766
♪ Take these broken wings
and learn to fly ♪

1035
00:55:19,865 --> 00:55:23,699
♪ All your life

1036
00:55:23,800 --> 00:55:28,333
♪ You were only waiting for
this moment to arise ♪

1037
00:55:28,432 --> 00:55:31,166
NARRATOR: It was peaceful, middle-class,

1038
00:55:31,266 --> 00:55:34,266
carefully focused on ending the war.

1039
00:55:34,365 --> 00:55:36,766
"It's nice," one marcher said,

1040
00:55:36,865 --> 00:55:38,599
"to go to a demonstration

1041
00:55:38,699 --> 00:55:43,632
without having to swear
allegiance to Chairman Mao."

1042
00:55:43,733 --> 00:55:45,166
♪ All your life

1043
00:55:45,266 --> 00:55:47,800
FRANK McGEE: Surely this is a
day unique in our history.

1044
00:55:47,900 --> 00:55:50,865
Never have so many of our people publicly

1045
00:55:50,965 --> 00:55:53,300
and collectively manifested opposition

1046
00:55:53,400 --> 00:55:56,532
to this country's involvement in a war.

1047
00:55:56,632 --> 00:55:59,565
It is unlikely we will remain unchanged.

1048
00:55:59,666 --> 00:56:02,500
Hundreds and hundreds of thousands

1049
00:56:02,599 --> 00:56:04,776
in cities from New York, with
its eight million people,

1050
00:56:04,800 --> 00:56:08,099
to Dubois, Wyoming, with its 800 people,

1051
00:56:08,199 --> 00:56:10,432
have sought to impress upon the president

1052
00:56:10,532 --> 00:56:12,599
their opposition to the war.

1053
00:56:12,699 --> 00:56:15,000
(bell rings)

1054
00:56:15,099 --> 00:56:21,900
CAROL CROCKER: The first large protest
march I went to was in Baltimore.

1055
00:56:22,000 --> 00:56:25,500
I'd never been with that
many people at one time.

1056
00:56:25,599 --> 00:56:31,666
Just the energy of the crowd
itself was tremendous.

1057
00:56:31,766 --> 00:56:34,065
I wondered if everybody was in it

1058
00:56:34,166 --> 00:56:36,132
for the right reasons.

1059
00:56:36,233 --> 00:56:40,865
I wasn't there to drink or smoke pot.

1060
00:56:40,965 --> 00:56:43,199
Not in those situations.

1061
00:56:43,300 --> 00:56:46,833
These, to me, were serious business.

1062
00:56:46,932 --> 00:56:50,400
This was the business of living life.

1063
00:56:50,500 --> 00:56:51,833
This was not a party.

1064
00:56:51,932 --> 00:56:54,666
I didn't just want to be with the crowd.

1065
00:56:54,766 --> 00:56:56,766
I didn't just want to make noise.

1066
00:56:56,865 --> 00:56:58,900
I wanted to make a difference.

1067
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:03,465
And I in no way wanted
to dishonor my brother.

1068
00:57:03,565 --> 00:57:05,099
♪ For this moment to arrive

1069
00:57:05,199 --> 00:57:07,199
QUINN: For most of the government today,

1070
00:57:07,300 --> 00:57:08,733
it was business as usual.

1071
00:57:08,833 --> 00:57:10,565
But at noon on the Capitol steps,

1072
00:57:10,666 --> 00:57:13,065
a thousand young congressional
staff employees

1073
00:57:13,166 --> 00:57:15,800
stood in silence for 45 minutes.

1074
00:57:15,900 --> 00:57:20,465
♪ Blackbird singing in
the dead of night ♪

1075
00:57:20,565 --> 00:57:23,965
NARRATOR: The children of several
of the president's closest aides

1076
00:57:24,065 --> 00:57:25,400
and cabinet members

1077
00:57:25,500 --> 00:57:28,166
took part in the national moratorium.

1078
00:57:28,266 --> 00:57:31,565
Vice President Agnew's 14-year-old daughter

1079
00:57:31,666 --> 00:57:33,300
wanted to march,

1080
00:57:33,400 --> 00:57:34,932
but he wouldn't let her.

1081
00:57:35,032 --> 00:57:37,032
Coretta Scott King,

1082
00:57:37,132 --> 00:57:40,000
the widow of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.,

1083
00:57:40,099 --> 00:57:42,833
led thousands of silent demonstrators

1084
00:57:42,932 --> 00:57:46,699
streaming past the White
House, where Nixon sat alone,

1085
00:57:46,800 --> 00:57:50,132
writing notes to himself on a yellow pad.

1086
00:57:50,233 --> 00:57:52,132
"Don't get rattled. Don't waver.

1087
00:57:52,233 --> 00:57:54,865
Don't react."

1088
00:57:57,465 --> 00:57:59,266
On November 3,

1089
00:57:59,365 --> 00:58:02,733
the president sought to
seize back the initiative.

1090
00:58:02,833 --> 00:58:04,632
Good evening, my fellow Americans.

1091
00:58:04,733 --> 00:58:08,599
NARRATOR: He went on national
television and called for patience

1092
00:58:08,699 --> 00:58:11,932
and asked Americans to rally behind him.

1093
00:58:12,032 --> 00:58:13,865
NIXON: To you,

1094
00:58:13,965 --> 00:58:18,233
the great silent majority
of my fellow Americans,

1095
00:58:18,333 --> 00:58:20,233
I ask for your support.

1096
00:58:20,333 --> 00:58:23,300
I pledged in my campaign for the presidency

1097
00:58:23,400 --> 00:58:24,865
to end the war

1098
00:58:24,965 --> 00:58:27,932
in a way that we could win the peace.

1099
00:58:28,032 --> 00:58:31,699
The more support I can have
from the American people,

1100
00:58:31,800 --> 00:58:33,833
the sooner that pledge can be redeemed;

1101
00:58:33,932 --> 00:58:37,365
for the more divided we are at home,

1102
00:58:37,465 --> 00:58:41,166
the less likely the enemy
is to negotiate at Paris.

1103
00:58:41,266 --> 00:58:42,575
("Okie From Muskogee" by
Merle Haggard playing)

1104
00:58:42,599 --> 00:58:44,965
Let us be united for peace.

1105
00:58:45,065 --> 00:58:49,300
♪ We don't smoke
marijuana in Muskogee ♪

1106
00:58:49,400 --> 00:58:51,532
NARRATOR: The speech was a triumph.

1107
00:58:51,632 --> 00:58:55,599
Nixon's approval rate soared to 68%.

1108
00:58:57,900 --> 00:59:00,266
MAN: All that's in the news

1109
00:59:00,365 --> 00:59:02,500
is the fact that the
moratoriums are meeting,

1110
00:59:02,599 --> 00:59:04,565
that our country's sick...

1111
00:59:04,666 --> 00:59:06,432
sick of this and sick of that.

1112
00:59:06,532 --> 00:59:09,166
It's young people are all the
ones that are standing up.

1113
00:59:09,266 --> 00:59:12,632
And there is a silent majority,
which is no longer silent.

1114
00:59:12,733 --> 00:59:15,965
We're the people who are wanting to show

1115
00:59:16,065 --> 00:59:18,965
that man deserves freedom
no matter where he is.

1116
00:59:19,065 --> 00:59:21,266
♪ A place where even
squares can have a ball ♪

1117
00:59:21,365 --> 00:59:23,900
Many brave men died in this
country to make it free...

1118
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:25,599
I believe that.

1119
00:59:25,699 --> 00:59:27,900
and let you... and let you have everything.

1120
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:31,233
SPIRO AGNEW: Senator Fulbright
said some months ago

1121
00:59:31,333 --> 00:59:33,833
that if the Vietnam War
went on much longer,

1122
00:59:33,932 --> 00:59:37,766
the best of our young
people would be in Canada.

1123
00:59:37,865 --> 00:59:40,733
Indeed, as for these deserters,

1124
00:59:40,833 --> 00:59:44,800
malcontents, radicals, incendiaries,

1125
00:59:44,900 --> 00:59:47,233
the civil and the uncivil disobedience

1126
00:59:47,333 --> 00:59:49,199
among our young,

1127
00:59:49,300 --> 00:59:51,166
SDS, PLP,

1128
00:59:51,266 --> 00:59:52,476
Weatherman one, Weatherman two,

1129
00:59:52,500 --> 00:59:54,699
the Revolutionary Action Movement,

1130
00:59:54,800 --> 00:59:56,900
Panthers, lions, hippies,

1131
00:59:57,000 --> 00:59:59,800
yippies, tigers alike.

1132
00:59:59,900 --> 01:00:02,365
I'd rather swap the whole damn zoo

1133
01:00:02,465 --> 01:00:04,932
for a single platoon of the
kind of young Americans

1134
01:00:05,032 --> 01:00:06,333
I saw in Vietnam.

1135
01:00:06,432 --> 01:00:09,300
(applause)

1136
01:00:09,400 --> 01:00:12,599
NARRATOR: "We've got the liberal
bastards on the run now,"

1137
01:00:12,699 --> 01:00:15,233
Nixon told his aides,

1138
01:00:15,333 --> 01:00:19,465
"and we're going to keep them on the run."

1139
01:00:19,565 --> 01:00:21,333
("My Son" by Jan Howard playing)

1140
01:00:29,632 --> 01:00:33,865
♪ My son, my son

1141
01:00:33,965 --> 01:00:35,932
JAN HOWARD: My doorbell rang,

1142
01:00:36,032 --> 01:00:38,199
and it was this guy standing there,

1143
01:00:38,300 --> 01:00:41,465
and he said, "Ms. Howard,
we're marching in Memphis

1144
01:00:41,565 --> 01:00:44,400
in protest of the Vietnam War."

1145
01:00:44,500 --> 01:00:46,465
I said, "Really?"

1146
01:00:46,565 --> 01:00:50,000
He said, "And we figured in
view of what happened..."

1147
01:00:50,099 --> 01:00:53,266
I said, "Yeah, my son's death."

1148
01:00:53,365 --> 01:00:56,199
He said, "Well, we thought
you'd like to join us."

1149
01:00:56,300 --> 01:00:58,565
I said, "One of the reasons he died

1150
01:00:58,666 --> 01:01:00,065
"was so you have the right.

1151
01:01:00,166 --> 01:01:02,932
"In this country, you have a right.

1152
01:01:03,032 --> 01:01:05,099
"Go right ahead and demonstrate.

1153
01:01:05,199 --> 01:01:07,166
Have at it."

1154
01:01:07,266 --> 01:01:09,632
I said, "But no, I won't be joining you."

1155
01:01:09,733 --> 01:01:11,365
I said, "But I'll tell you what.

1156
01:01:11,465 --> 01:01:13,199
"If you ever ring my doorbell again,

1157
01:01:13,300 --> 01:01:16,300
I will blow your damn head
off with a .357 Magnum."

1158
01:01:26,632 --> 01:01:28,900
TIM O'BRIEN: Well, I was
stationed in Vietnam

1159
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:32,400
at a province called Quang Ngai.

1160
01:01:32,500 --> 01:01:34,100
Even back during the time of the French,

1161
01:01:34,132 --> 01:01:38,099
it was a very heavily Viet Minh area,

1162
01:01:38,199 --> 01:01:40,666
and, when I arrived, heavily Viet Cong.

1163
01:01:43,333 --> 01:01:46,900
NARRATOR: No province suffered
more during the American war

1164
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:49,365
than the coastal province of Quang Ngai.

1165
01:01:49,465 --> 01:01:51,432
(artillery fire)

1166
01:01:51,532 --> 01:01:56,333
More than 70% of its villages
had been shelled by Navy ships,

1167
01:01:56,432 --> 01:02:00,266
bombed, bulldozed, or burned to the ground,

1168
01:02:00,365 --> 01:02:02,733
and more than 40% of its people

1169
01:02:02,833 --> 01:02:05,400
had been forced into refugee camps

1170
01:02:05,500 --> 01:02:08,965
before Tim O'Brien from
Worthington, Minnesota,

1171
01:02:09,065 --> 01:02:11,465
got there in 1969.

1172
01:02:13,500 --> 01:02:15,180
O'BRIEN: It was a province that was viewed

1173
01:02:15,266 --> 01:02:17,632
much as I guess many Americans might view,

1174
01:02:17,733 --> 01:02:19,965
you know, sort of redneck America.

1175
01:02:20,065 --> 01:02:23,432
Sort of country bumpkins.

1176
01:02:23,532 --> 01:02:24,908
And they may have been country bumpkins,

1177
01:02:24,932 --> 01:02:27,333
but they were fiercely independent.

1178
01:02:27,432 --> 01:02:30,800
NARRATOR: Private O'Brien
served in Alpha Company,

1179
01:02:30,900 --> 01:02:35,500
3rd Platoon, 5th Battalion,
23rd Americal Division,

1180
01:02:35,599 --> 01:02:38,733
headquartered at a landing
zone called Gator,

1181
01:02:38,833 --> 01:02:42,099
"30 or 40 acres of almost-America,"

1182
01:02:42,199 --> 01:02:43,833
O'Brien remembered,

1183
01:02:43,932 --> 01:02:47,166
with hot showers and cold beer.

1184
01:02:48,865 --> 01:02:50,565
O'BRIEN: There was no sense of mission.

1185
01:02:50,666 --> 01:02:52,199
There was no sense of daily purpose.

1186
01:02:52,300 --> 01:02:54,432
We didn't know why we were in a village

1187
01:02:54,532 --> 01:02:56,666
or what we were supposed to accomplish.

1188
01:02:56,766 --> 01:02:58,932
So we'd kick around jugs of rice

1189
01:02:59,032 --> 01:03:01,900
and search houses and frisk people,

1190
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:04,333
and not knowing what we were looking for

1191
01:03:04,432 --> 01:03:07,833
and rarely finding anything.

1192
01:03:07,932 --> 01:03:09,166
And somebody might die,

1193
01:03:09,266 --> 01:03:11,065
one of our guys, and somebody might not.

1194
01:03:11,166 --> 01:03:13,532
Then we'd come back to the
same village a week later

1195
01:03:13,632 --> 01:03:15,865
or two weeks later, do it all over again.

1196
01:03:15,965 --> 01:03:18,733
It was like chasing ghosts.

1197
01:03:18,833 --> 01:03:21,132
(helicopter blades whirring)

1198
01:03:22,800 --> 01:03:24,599
NARRATOR: An American APC

1199
01:03:24,699 --> 01:03:28,166
accidentally crushed one man
from O'Brien's company.

1200
01:03:28,266 --> 01:03:32,465
An enemy grenade skittered off
O'Brien's helmet and exploded,

1201
01:03:32,565 --> 01:03:35,965
wounding a G.I. standing a few feet away.

1202
01:03:38,900 --> 01:03:42,900
But mines and booby traps
were the greatest menace.

1203
01:03:49,400 --> 01:03:51,900
O'BRIEN: Somewhere around
80% of our casualties

1204
01:03:52,000 --> 01:03:54,465
came from land mines of all sorts.

1205
01:03:56,166 --> 01:03:59,099
In Vietnam, for me, just
to get up in the morning

1206
01:03:59,199 --> 01:04:02,400
and look out at the land and think,

1207
01:04:02,500 --> 01:04:05,300
"In a few minutes I'll
be walking out there,

1208
01:04:05,400 --> 01:04:08,266
"and will my corpse be there or there?

1209
01:04:08,365 --> 01:04:11,565
Will I lose a leg out there?"

1210
01:04:11,666 --> 01:04:15,900
I'd always thought of courage
as charging enemy bunkers

1211
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:18,266
or standing up under fire.

1212
01:04:18,365 --> 01:04:21,699
But just to walk through Quang Ngai,

1213
01:04:21,800 --> 01:04:24,065
day after day, from village to village,

1214
01:04:24,166 --> 01:04:28,432
and through the paddies and
up into the mountains,

1215
01:04:28,532 --> 01:04:32,065
just to make your legs
move was an act of courage

1216
01:04:32,166 --> 01:04:34,833
that if, say, you were
living in Sioux City,

1217
01:04:34,932 --> 01:04:36,565
it wouldn't be courageous

1218
01:04:36,666 --> 01:04:39,166
to walk to the grocery
store or down Main Street,

1219
01:04:39,266 --> 01:04:41,865
you know, just to have your
legs go back and forth.

1220
01:04:41,965 --> 01:04:43,599
But in Vietnam, for me,

1221
01:04:43,699 --> 01:04:45,800
just to walk felt incredibly brave.

1222
01:04:45,900 --> 01:04:48,365
I would sometimes look
at my legs as I walked,

1223
01:04:48,465 --> 01:04:50,432
thinking, "How am I doing this?"

1224
01:04:53,233 --> 01:04:55,132
BAO NINH:

1225
01:05:22,766 --> 01:05:25,000
NARRATOR: Bao Ninh was 17

1226
01:05:25,099 --> 01:05:27,900
when he was drafted into
the North Vietnamese Army

1227
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:29,099
to fight the Americans,

1228
01:05:29,199 --> 01:05:32,465
just as his father had fought the French.

1229
01:05:32,565 --> 01:05:35,800
His war would take place
in the Central Highlands

1230
01:05:35,900 --> 01:05:38,032
of South Vietnam.

1231
01:05:38,132 --> 01:05:40,233
It was American firepower

1232
01:05:40,333 --> 01:05:44,932
that Bao Ninh and his fellow
soldiers feared the most.

1233
01:05:45,032 --> 01:05:45,699
(explosion)

1234
01:05:45,800 --> 01:05:47,733
BAO NINH:

1235
01:07:13,132 --> 01:07:14,500
(explosion)

1236
01:08:04,300 --> 01:08:06,699
(birds chirping, squawking)

1237
01:08:10,332 --> 01:08:12,399
NARRATOR: Back in the spring,

1238
01:08:12,500 --> 01:08:15,932
Tim O'Brien's outfit had been
sent into an area of operations

1239
01:08:16,033 --> 01:08:18,800
the Americans called "Pinkville,"

1240
01:08:18,899 --> 01:08:20,733
clusters of villages

1241
01:08:20,832 --> 01:08:24,199
that included a hamlet they called My Lai.

1242
01:08:26,065 --> 01:08:28,199
O'BRIEN: We hated going there.

1243
01:08:28,300 --> 01:08:31,065
When we'd get the word, "You're
headed for Pinkville,"

1244
01:08:31,166 --> 01:08:33,175
one guy would say to another,
"Somebody's gonna die,"

1245
01:08:33,199 --> 01:08:34,559
or, "Somebody's gonna lose a leg."

1246
01:08:34,632 --> 01:08:36,632
We were terrified of the place.

1247
01:08:36,733 --> 01:08:40,166
It was littered with land mines.

1248
01:08:40,265 --> 01:08:42,166
The villagers were...

1249
01:08:42,265 --> 01:08:44,065
The expressions on their faces,

1250
01:08:44,166 --> 01:08:48,466
including the children of,
say, six or five years old,

1251
01:08:48,565 --> 01:08:53,733
had a mixture of hostility and terror.

1252
01:08:56,033 --> 01:08:57,500
I can't say many of the villagers

1253
01:08:57,600 --> 01:08:59,632
came with open arms to us,

1254
01:08:59,733 --> 01:09:01,765
but this place was special.

1255
01:09:01,865 --> 01:09:03,865
And I remember talking to fellow soldiers,

1256
01:09:03,966 --> 01:09:06,233
thinking, "What is it with this place?"

1257
01:09:07,600 --> 01:09:09,632
And then about three-quarters of the way

1258
01:09:09,733 --> 01:09:11,365
through my tour in Vietnam,

1259
01:09:11,466 --> 01:09:14,666
the story of the My Lai
Massacre broke in the States.

1260
01:09:15,966 --> 01:09:18,966
NARRATOR: On November 12, 1969,

1261
01:09:19,065 --> 01:09:21,600
the Dispatch News Service in Washington

1262
01:09:21,699 --> 01:09:25,733
moved a story by investigative
journalist Seymour Hersh.

1263
01:09:27,033 --> 01:09:29,265
It was soon followed by the publication

1264
01:09:29,365 --> 01:09:34,332
of graphic photos taken by Army
photographer Ronald Haeberle.

1265
01:09:35,800 --> 01:09:39,632
The story and the pictures
stunned the country.

1266
01:09:39,733 --> 01:09:41,365
HUNTLEY: Charges have been made

1267
01:09:41,466 --> 01:09:44,199
that troops of the Americal Division

1268
01:09:44,300 --> 01:09:47,733
killed as many as 567 South
Vietnamese civilians

1269
01:09:47,832 --> 01:09:51,000
during a sweep in March 1968.

1270
01:09:52,265 --> 01:09:54,233
NARRATOR: 20 months earlier,

1271
01:09:54,332 --> 01:09:57,800
on the morning of March 16, 1968,

1272
01:09:57,899 --> 01:10:00,500
105 men from a rifle company

1273
01:10:00,600 --> 01:10:02,765
belonging to the Americal Division,

1274
01:10:02,865 --> 01:10:04,966
and led by Captain Ernest Medina

1275
01:10:05,065 --> 01:10:07,199
and Lieutenant William Calley,

1276
01:10:07,300 --> 01:10:11,399
had been ordered to helicopter
into the village of My Lai 4.

1277
01:10:12,733 --> 01:10:15,966
Since arriving in Vietnam,
they had lost 28 men

1278
01:10:16,065 --> 01:10:20,932
to mines and booby traps
and unseen snipers.

1279
01:10:21,033 --> 01:10:25,832
Two days earlier, a popular
squad leader had been killed.

1280
01:10:25,932 --> 01:10:29,600
They had been told a unit
of main-force Viet Cong

1281
01:10:29,699 --> 01:10:31,365
was waiting for them,

1282
01:10:31,466 --> 01:10:34,233
and they were eager for revenge.

1283
01:10:35,500 --> 01:10:38,000
But they received no hostile fire,

1284
01:10:38,100 --> 01:10:42,966
encountered no enemy soldiers.

1285
01:10:44,432 --> 01:10:47,733
Instead, over the next four hours,

1286
01:10:47,832 --> 01:10:50,666
Medina, Calley, and their men murdered

1287
01:10:50,765 --> 01:10:58,500
407 defenseless old men,
women, children, and infants.

1288
01:11:08,466 --> 01:11:11,132
Many of the women and girls were raped

1289
01:11:11,233 --> 01:11:13,533
before they were shot.

1290
01:11:16,600 --> 01:11:18,899
There would have been still more slaughter

1291
01:11:19,000 --> 01:11:23,166
had a helicopter pilot named
Hugh Thompson, Jr., not landed

1292
01:11:23,265 --> 01:11:26,666
between the men and some
of their intended targets

1293
01:11:26,765 --> 01:11:30,399
and ordered his crew to open
fire on their fellow Americans

1294
01:11:30,500 --> 01:11:33,765
if they did not stop shooting civilians.

1295
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:40,533
At the same time, just a mile or so away,

1296
01:11:40,632 --> 01:11:45,332
another company murdered 97 more villagers.

1297
01:11:47,332 --> 01:11:50,365
O'BRIEN: And suddenly it was
like a window shade going up,

1298
01:11:50,466 --> 01:11:51,899
and then there's light,

1299
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:54,065
and we understood what had engendered

1300
01:11:54,166 --> 01:11:57,500
this horror in these kids' faces

1301
01:11:57,600 --> 01:12:00,332
and fear and the... and the hatred.

1302
01:12:00,432 --> 01:12:03,966
Hundred and some American
soldiers in four hours or so

1303
01:12:04,065 --> 01:12:06,733
butchering innocent people,

1304
01:12:06,832 --> 01:12:08,899
in all kinds of ways... machine-gunning them

1305
01:12:09,000 --> 01:12:11,300
and throwing them in
wells and scalping them

1306
01:12:11,399 --> 01:12:13,265
and killing them in ditches

1307
01:12:13,365 --> 01:12:15,966
and taking a lunch break and
then doing it some more.

1308
01:12:17,100 --> 01:12:19,233
Systematic homicide.

1309
01:12:19,332 --> 01:12:20,865
MIKE WALLACE: What kind of people?

1310
01:12:20,966 --> 01:12:21,966
Men, women, children?

1311
01:12:22,065 --> 01:12:23,500
PAUL MEADLO: Men, women, children.

1312
01:12:23,600 --> 01:12:25,300
WALLACE: Babies? MEADLO: Babies.

1313
01:12:25,399 --> 01:12:27,233
Uh, Lieutenant Calley came over and said,

1314
01:12:27,332 --> 01:12:29,233
"You know what to do with them, don't you?"

1315
01:12:29,332 --> 01:12:30,832
And, uh, I said, "Yes."

1316
01:12:30,932 --> 01:12:34,932
So l took it for granted that he
just wanted us to watch them.

1317
01:12:35,033 --> 01:12:36,800
And he left and came back

1318
01:12:36,899 --> 01:12:39,466
about ten or... ten or 15 minutes later,

1319
01:12:39,565 --> 01:12:43,800
and said, "How come you
ain't, uh, killed them yet?"

1320
01:12:43,899 --> 01:12:45,466
You killed how many at that time?

1321
01:12:45,565 --> 01:12:48,065
Well, I fired my automatic, so, uh...

1322
01:12:48,166 --> 01:12:50,800
you can't, uh... you just
spray the area on them,

1323
01:12:50,899 --> 01:12:53,265
so you really can't know
how many you killed

1324
01:12:53,365 --> 01:12:56,166
because it comes out so doggone fast.

1325
01:12:56,265 --> 01:13:00,500
So I, I might've killed
about, uh, ten or 15 of them.

1326
01:13:01,632 --> 01:13:03,132
Men, women, and children?

1327
01:13:03,233 --> 01:13:04,800
Men, women, and children.

1328
01:13:04,899 --> 01:13:06,966
And babies? And babies.

1329
01:13:08,432 --> 01:13:10,332
Why did I do it?

1330
01:13:10,432 --> 01:13:13,233
Because I felt like I was ordered to do it.

1331
01:13:13,332 --> 01:13:15,899
And it seemed like, uh...

1332
01:13:18,600 --> 01:13:22,533
Well, at the time, I felt like
I was doing the right thing.

1333
01:13:22,632 --> 01:13:24,533
I really did.

1334
01:13:24,632 --> 01:13:27,699
Because, uh, like I said, I lost buddies,

1335
01:13:27,800 --> 01:13:29,699
I lost... I lost a good...

1336
01:13:29,800 --> 01:13:34,166
damn good buddy... Bobby Wilson...

1337
01:13:34,265 --> 01:13:37,932
and it was on my conscience,
and it was on...

1338
01:13:38,033 --> 01:13:40,000
So after I done it, I felt good.

1339
01:13:40,100 --> 01:13:44,332
But later on that day,
it was getting to me.

1340
01:13:44,432 --> 01:13:47,500
It's so hard, I think, for
a good many Americans

1341
01:13:47,600 --> 01:13:50,632
to understand that young, capable,

1342
01:13:50,733 --> 01:13:54,000
brave American boys

1343
01:13:54,100 --> 01:13:57,033
could line up

1344
01:13:57,132 --> 01:14:01,733
old men, women, children, and babies

1345
01:14:01,832 --> 01:14:04,565
and shoot them down in cold blood.

1346
01:14:09,300 --> 01:14:11,533
How do you explain that?

1347
01:14:11,632 --> 01:14:13,565
I wouldn't know.

1348
01:14:19,500 --> 01:14:21,399
(low, distant chatter)

1349
01:14:23,666 --> 01:14:27,733
NARRATOR: The killing of civilians
has happened in every war.

1350
01:14:27,832 --> 01:14:32,132
In Vietnam, it was not policy or routine,

1351
01:14:32,233 --> 01:14:34,865
but it was not an aberration, either.

1352
01:14:36,432 --> 01:14:41,332
Still, the scale and
deliberateness and intimacy

1353
01:14:41,432 --> 01:14:43,565
of what happened at My Lai

1354
01:14:43,666 --> 01:14:44,966
was different.

1355
01:14:45,065 --> 01:14:46,699
SHEEHAN: It was different

1356
01:14:46,800 --> 01:14:49,533
because they were killing
Vietnamese point-blank

1357
01:14:49,632 --> 01:14:51,000
with rifles and grenades.

1358
01:14:51,100 --> 01:14:53,432
They were murdering them directly.

1359
01:14:53,533 --> 01:14:55,800
They weren't doing it
with bombs and artillery.

1360
01:14:55,899 --> 01:14:57,408
If they'd been doing it
with bombs and artillery,

1361
01:14:57,432 --> 01:14:58,576
nobody would have said a word,

1362
01:14:58,600 --> 01:15:00,080
because it was going on all the time.

1363
01:15:01,033 --> 01:15:02,332
NARRATOR: Not every soldier

1364
01:15:02,432 --> 01:15:04,166
participated in the killings that day.

1365
01:15:04,265 --> 01:15:07,800
Some led villagers away to safety.

1366
01:15:07,899 --> 01:15:10,666
But a failure of military leadership

1367
01:15:10,765 --> 01:15:13,865
at nearly every level had
created the conditions

1368
01:15:13,966 --> 01:15:17,365
that made the massacre possible.

1369
01:15:17,466 --> 01:15:21,699
The My Lai story might have
shocked the American public,

1370
01:15:21,800 --> 01:15:24,000
but it was not news to the Army.

1371
01:15:24,100 --> 01:15:27,199
It had occurred almost two years before,

1372
01:15:27,300 --> 01:15:30,365
just after the Tet Offensive.

1373
01:15:30,466 --> 01:15:32,832
Hugh Thompson, the helicopter pilot

1374
01:15:32,932 --> 01:15:35,000
who had tried to stop the massacre,

1375
01:15:35,100 --> 01:15:37,932
reported what he had seen,

1376
01:15:38,033 --> 01:15:39,932
but no one in the chain of command

1377
01:15:40,033 --> 01:15:41,265
was willing to act.

1378
01:15:41,365 --> 01:15:45,000
The slaughter was covered up.

1379
01:15:45,100 --> 01:15:48,865
Later, an ex-corporal
named Ronald Ridenhour,

1380
01:15:48,966 --> 01:15:50,632
who had heard about what had happened

1381
01:15:50,733 --> 01:15:52,666
from several men who had been there,

1382
01:15:52,765 --> 01:15:56,233
wrote letters to the president
of the United States,

1383
01:15:56,332 --> 01:15:58,132
the secretary of defense,

1384
01:15:58,233 --> 01:16:02,132
and more than two dozen other
high-ranking officials.

1385
01:16:02,233 --> 01:16:05,399
STAN ATKINSON: Personally,
what decision-making process

1386
01:16:05,500 --> 01:16:08,300
did you go through before you
decided to take your action?

1387
01:16:08,399 --> 01:16:12,065
I guess I just wrestled
with my own conscience

1388
01:16:12,166 --> 01:16:14,432
to try to decide what action to take.

1389
01:16:14,533 --> 01:16:16,565
I felt that I had to take some action.

1390
01:16:16,666 --> 01:16:18,033
I had to do something.

1391
01:16:18,132 --> 01:16:19,365
I couldn't just...

1392
01:16:19,466 --> 01:16:22,000
just rest with this knowledge
for the rest of my life

1393
01:16:22,100 --> 01:16:24,932
that I couldn't... I couldn't
live with myself if I did.

1394
01:16:25,033 --> 01:16:27,932
NARRATOR: President Nixon's first reaction

1395
01:16:28,033 --> 01:16:32,166
was to investigate those who
reported the slaughter.

1396
01:16:32,265 --> 01:16:34,966
"It's those dirty rotten Jews from New York

1397
01:16:35,065 --> 01:16:36,332
who are behind it,"

1398
01:16:36,432 --> 01:16:37,865
he told an aide.

1399
01:16:37,966 --> 01:16:42,300
Eventually, Lieutenant
General William R. Peers,

1400
01:16:42,399 --> 01:16:46,233
a veteran of 30 months as a
troop commander in Vietnam,

1401
01:16:46,332 --> 01:16:48,033
was assigned to head a panel

1402
01:16:48,132 --> 01:16:50,932
to look into what had really happened.

1403
01:16:51,033 --> 01:16:54,166
Peers found that 30 persons,

1404
01:16:54,265 --> 01:16:56,600
including the division commander,

1405
01:16:56,699 --> 01:16:58,932
General Samuel W. Koster,

1406
01:16:59,033 --> 01:17:01,332
had either committed atrocities

1407
01:17:01,432 --> 01:17:05,399
or had conspired to cover them up.

1408
01:17:09,399 --> 01:17:13,132
Peers had wanted to call
My Lai a "massacre."

1409
01:17:13,233 --> 01:17:16,500
His superiors made him use the phrase,

1410
01:17:16,600 --> 01:17:20,632
"a tragedy of major proportions."

1411
01:17:20,733 --> 01:17:26,166
In the end, the Army indicted
25 officers and men,

1412
01:17:26,265 --> 01:17:31,432
including the platoon leader,
Lieutenant William Calley.

1413
01:17:34,000 --> 01:17:36,000
VALLELY: Calley's a killer.

1414
01:17:36,100 --> 01:17:38,033
Calley's a murderer

1415
01:17:38,132 --> 01:17:40,399
and a... a sick person.

1416
01:17:42,500 --> 01:17:45,533
I'm not gonna be in any, you know, uh,

1417
01:17:45,632 --> 01:17:48,065
propaganda movie for the
United States Marine Corps,

1418
01:17:48,166 --> 01:17:50,100
but we didn't have that guy.

1419
01:17:52,365 --> 01:17:54,865
We had individuals who, who...

1420
01:17:54,966 --> 01:17:56,932
who committed war crimes, of course.

1421
01:17:57,033 --> 01:18:01,000
And, um, you know, I wanted to kill them.

1422
01:18:01,100 --> 01:18:03,600
I sometimes wish I did kill 'em.

1423
01:18:06,432 --> 01:18:10,199
But... I was afraid to kill 'em.

1424
01:18:12,600 --> 01:18:14,533
♪ Two, one, two, three, four

1425
01:18:14,632 --> 01:18:17,332
("Give Peace a Chance" by
The Plastic Ono Band plays)

1426
01:18:17,432 --> 01:18:19,932
(loud crowd chatter)

1427
01:18:20,033 --> 01:18:21,565
♪ Everybody's talking about...

1428
01:18:21,666 --> 01:18:24,800
ZIMMERMAN: I never considered
the Vietnamese our enemy.

1429
01:18:24,899 --> 01:18:26,500
They had never done anything

1430
01:18:26,600 --> 01:18:29,166
to threaten the security
of the United States.

1431
01:18:29,265 --> 01:18:32,000
They were off 10,000 miles away,

1432
01:18:32,100 --> 01:18:33,832
minding their own business,

1433
01:18:33,932 --> 01:18:36,300
and we went there to their country,

1434
01:18:36,399 --> 01:18:37,865
told them what kind of government

1435
01:18:37,966 --> 01:18:40,233
we wanted them to have.

1436
01:18:40,332 --> 01:18:44,533
JAMES WILLBANKS: Well, when
I see the war protesters,

1437
01:18:44,632 --> 01:18:46,399
I react on a couple of levels.

1438
01:18:46,500 --> 01:18:49,033
Intellectually, I certainly
understand their right

1439
01:18:49,132 --> 01:18:50,832
to the freedom of speech.

1440
01:18:50,932 --> 01:18:52,332
But I will tell you

1441
01:18:52,432 --> 01:18:55,399
that when I see them waving NLF flags,

1442
01:18:55,500 --> 01:18:58,733
the enemy that I and my
friends had to fight,

1443
01:18:58,832 --> 01:19:02,033
and some of my friends had to die fighting,

1444
01:19:02,132 --> 01:19:03,765
that doesn't sit very well with me.

1445
01:19:03,865 --> 01:19:07,000
♪ All we are saying...

1446
01:19:07,100 --> 01:19:10,033
NARRATOR: On November 15, 1969,

1447
01:19:10,132 --> 01:19:12,365
half a million citizens turned out

1448
01:19:12,466 --> 01:19:15,000
against the war in Washington, again.

1449
01:19:15,100 --> 01:19:17,399
♪ Everybody's talking
about revolution... ♪

1450
01:19:17,500 --> 01:19:20,733
NARRATOR: This time, buses
provided an impenetrable wall

1451
01:19:20,832 --> 01:19:23,033
around the White House.

1452
01:19:23,132 --> 01:19:25,500
President Nixon claimed he was too busy

1453
01:19:25,600 --> 01:19:27,666
watching football on television

1454
01:19:27,765 --> 01:19:29,000
to pay attention,

1455
01:19:29,100 --> 01:19:33,533
but he did suggest that Army
helicopters might be used

1456
01:19:33,632 --> 01:19:35,533
to blow out the marchers' candles.

1457
01:19:35,632 --> 01:19:37,632
♪ All we are saying...

1458
01:19:37,733 --> 01:19:39,166
(car horns honking)

1459
01:19:39,265 --> 01:19:41,375
NARRATOR: Hundreds of thousands
of others demonstrated

1460
01:19:41,399 --> 01:19:44,899
in San Francisco and New York.

1461
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:46,632
(indistinct shouting)

1462
01:19:46,733 --> 01:19:49,632
(cheering and whistling,
indistinct shouting)

1463
01:19:52,166 --> 01:19:54,533
The most striking antiwar protest

1464
01:19:54,632 --> 01:19:55,865
of this Thanksgiving Day

1465
01:19:55,966 --> 01:19:58,432
occurred not in this
country, but in Vietnam,

1466
01:19:58,533 --> 01:20:00,932
though its form was uniquely American.

1467
01:20:01,033 --> 01:20:03,132
About 100 American soldiers

1468
01:20:03,233 --> 01:20:05,632
stationed at a hospital in Pleiku

1469
01:20:05,733 --> 01:20:08,300
refused to eat their
traditional turkey dinner.

1470
01:20:08,399 --> 01:20:12,365
They described their fast as a
passive protest against the war.

1471
01:20:14,166 --> 01:20:16,600
("Born Under a Bad Sign" by Booker T.
and the M.G.'s plays)

1472
01:20:21,132 --> 01:20:22,800
The Army did what the Army does.

1473
01:20:22,899 --> 01:20:24,442
Every year, you know, for Thanksgiving,

1474
01:20:24,466 --> 01:20:25,632
they make a big deal.

1475
01:20:25,733 --> 01:20:26,908
They're gonna bring in turkey,

1476
01:20:26,932 --> 01:20:28,375
they're gonna bring in mashed potatoes,

1477
01:20:28,399 --> 01:20:30,733
and apple pie and whatever.

1478
01:20:30,832 --> 01:20:32,733
And by this point, I think,

1479
01:20:32,832 --> 01:20:35,765
a lot of us were very,
very cynical about the war

1480
01:20:35,865 --> 01:20:37,699
and what was going on.

1481
01:20:37,800 --> 01:20:41,265
But we weren't gonna make
a big deal about it.

1482
01:20:41,365 --> 01:20:43,932
We knew there were gonna
be TV people there.

1483
01:20:44,033 --> 01:20:47,166
And a couple of the organizers
were looking for people to talk.

1484
01:20:47,265 --> 01:20:48,899
They came to me, I said, "No."

1485
01:20:49,000 --> 01:20:51,332
I said, "Look, I'm gonna
fast and do my thing."

1486
01:20:51,432 --> 01:20:53,300
I said, "But I, I really don't want

1487
01:20:53,399 --> 01:20:55,800
to be involved with any media thing."

1488
01:20:55,899 --> 01:21:00,300
NARRATOR: That Thanksgiving Day,
Lieutenant Furey was on duty

1489
01:21:00,399 --> 01:21:04,466
when one of her patients took
a sudden turn for the worse.

1490
01:21:04,565 --> 01:21:07,565
FUREY: Some patients, they
just get into your heart.

1491
01:21:07,666 --> 01:21:09,265
And this kid, I think he was 18.

1492
01:21:09,365 --> 01:21:10,800
His name was Timmy.

1493
01:21:10,899 --> 01:21:15,332
It was unlikely he was gonna survive.

1494
01:21:15,432 --> 01:21:18,899
And I just got so angry.

1495
01:21:19,000 --> 01:21:22,432
I just lost it.

1496
01:21:22,533 --> 01:21:24,632
I remember walking out of the O.R.,

1497
01:21:24,733 --> 01:21:26,608
I ripped off the gown, and
I ripped off the mask,

1498
01:21:26,632 --> 01:21:29,899
I walked outside, I said,
"Where are those reporters?"

1499
01:21:43,033 --> 01:21:45,175
I mean, you know, you don't
demonstrate against the war

1500
01:21:45,199 --> 01:21:46,332
in a war zone.

1501
01:21:46,432 --> 01:21:49,332
By that time, of course,
you, you had the attitude,

1502
01:21:49,432 --> 01:21:51,265
"What are they gonna do?

1503
01:21:51,365 --> 01:21:53,332
Send me to Vietnam?"

1504
01:21:56,800 --> 01:22:00,332
(loud, overlapping chatter and shouting)

1505
01:22:00,432 --> 01:22:03,166
(indistinct chanting)

1506
01:22:03,265 --> 01:22:06,199
JOHN MUSGRAVE: Let's just say that
being a Marine combat veteran

1507
01:22:06,300 --> 01:22:10,265
on a college campus in 1969 and 1970...

1508
01:22:10,365 --> 01:22:12,132
it wasn't a real good thing to be

1509
01:22:12,233 --> 01:22:14,300
if you wanted to get dates and be popular.

1510
01:22:17,065 --> 01:22:20,533
When I came home, it seemed like

1511
01:22:20,632 --> 01:22:23,966
I didn't have anything
to give to anybody else.

1512
01:22:27,332 --> 01:22:31,365
NARRATOR: Marine Corporal John
Musgrave had very nearly died

1513
01:22:31,466 --> 01:22:36,100
in combat below the DMZ
in the autumn of 1967.

1514
01:22:36,199 --> 01:22:39,000
Wounded in the jaw and shoulder,

1515
01:22:39,100 --> 01:22:42,865
his ribs shattered, lung
pierced, nerves cut,

1516
01:22:42,966 --> 01:22:47,300
he had spent 17 months in Navy hospitals.

1517
01:22:47,399 --> 01:22:50,432
He was now studying at Baker University

1518
01:22:50,533 --> 01:22:53,300
in Baldwin City, Kansas.

1519
01:22:53,399 --> 01:22:55,699
(indistinct chanting and shouting)

1520
01:22:55,800 --> 01:23:00,199
But wherever he went, the
war was never far away.

1521
01:23:02,432 --> 01:23:06,765
MUSGRAVE: And the peace movement,
for a while, got real nasty,

1522
01:23:06,865 --> 01:23:08,865
calling veterans baby killers.

1523
01:23:10,932 --> 01:23:12,765
It did more than piss us off.

1524
01:23:12,865 --> 01:23:14,699
It broke our hearts.

1525
